_args). Repeat with different test suites and failure messages to confirm the pattern. This is a deterministic test of prompt construction logic, not LLM behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a deterministic loop-control behavior. Mock the LLM to always return code that fails all tests. Run the service and verify it makes exactly 3 LLM calls, runs tests 3 times, and exits with a structured error containing all 3 attempts' results. The test does not depend on real LLM non-determinism; we control failure outcomes via the mock. We are testing that the counter/loop limit works correctly, not LLM behavior.","test_description":"Mock the LLM to return code that fails all provided tests on every call. Run the service. Verify the service makes exactly 3 LLM calls (no more, no fewer), executes the test suite 3 times, and returns a structured error object containing all 3 attempts with their test failure results. Assert that it does not make a 4th call. Verify the error structure includes attempt numbers, generated code snippets, and test output for each attempt.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full loop — generate, test, refine, test again — produces a working implementation for a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"The phrase 'a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong' is crucial. This requires identifying a function where the real LLM has <50% first-attempt success rate, then demonstrating the refinement loop improves the outcome. Only a real LLM can establish that difficulty baseline. Mocking to fail-then-pass does not test real refinement behavior; it fabricates artificial difficulty. The loop is multi-step (generate → test → refine → test), and success depends on whether the real LLM actually learns from failure feedback across iterations.","test_description":"First, baseline: run 15+ raw LLM calls on a moderately complex function (no refinement loop) and confirm <50% first-attempt success. Then, run the service's full refinement loop 15+ times on the same function. Verify that the loop achieves significantly higher success rate (target >80%), proving that refinement adds value for functions the LLM initially struggles with. Document: baseline success rate vs. loop success rate. This demonstrates the loop works for hard cases where single LLM calls fail.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.85}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13735,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13735},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ec1acbab-054a-4f31-a0af-cc32c78f2121","uuid":"e1124a64-f3cc-4e2e-92af-ff64a7f3ba4a"}
